04:20:18.600 --> 04:20:29.600
So we started that project and two years after we started it, we erected that statue.

04:20:29.600 --> 04:20:34.600
Still no work in progress.

04:20:34.600 --> 04:20:40.600
I've seen when I first came to the grave, it was just a little crime scene.

04:20:40.600 --> 04:20:44.600
Yeah, see all of that other land around there was a part of Mrs. Hamon.

04:20:44.600 --> 04:20:59.600
We donated, in order to get her buried there, we donated all of that land to the city of Ingenola, not in to city of Ruleville, Mississippi, in order to create that special burial site for her.

04:20:59.600 --> 04:21:04.600
And so the city of Ruleville, Mississippi owned the rest of that land.

04:21:04.600 --> 04:21:10.600
You know, when they've used it as, I guess, to help economic development.

04:21:10.600 --> 04:21:20.600
But it was really our intention that that land all become a part of Mrs. Hamer's burial site.

04:21:20.600 --> 04:21:28.600
We expect to have a move our museum into a building that we would erect down there.

04:21:28.600 --> 04:21:37.600
And that we would have a paved parking area out there, a beautiful area parking.

04:21:37.600 --> 04:21:43.600
So we ain't told the city about that yet.

04:21:44.600 --> 04:21:53.600
Yeah, my grandmother used to always tell me, she said, to foretell is to forewarn.

04:21:53.600 --> 04:22:02.600
As you know, James Meredith, the first black to know and let graduate from Ole Miss.

04:22:02.600 --> 04:22:04.600
Graduated.

04:22:04.600 --> 04:22:08.600
You know, there was a big flare up up there while he was dead and some people were killed.

04:22:08.600 --> 04:22:13.600
But he later graduated from New York, I think, in New York.

04:22:13.600 --> 04:22:33.600
And then after he was back for a while, and a few other prizes, he decided to walk from the Tennessee State Line to Jackson, Mississippi to encourage voter registration and black participation, political participation.

04:22:33.600 --> 04:22:36.600
And he called it a march against fear.

04:22:36.600 --> 04:22:47.600
So on a particular day in June 1966, James Meredith stepped off on his walk alone.

04:22:47.600 --> 04:22:54.600
And after he had gone a short distance, he was shot down from ambush by a white person.

04:22:55.600 --> 04:23:06.600
While he's in the hospital recuperating Dr. King and Floyd McKissick of CORE, and Stokely Carmichael Michael,

04:23:06.600 --> 04:23:22.600
who had just become chairperson of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, succeeding John Lewis, met with Meredith and got his approval to continue the march alone.

04:23:22.600 --> 04:23:29.600
Highway 51 into Jackson, Mississippi, where there would be a big rabbit.

04:23:29.600 --> 04:23:45.600
So the march took off from where Meredith was shot down and was headed to Grenada, Mississippi, Mississippi, that was going to be their first overnight state.

04:23:46.600 --> 04:24:01.600
And Fannie Lou Hamer Hamer, who had been talked with Stokely Carmichael and Dr. King and others about the march, had she wasn't able to be there because of other speaking engagements.

04:24:02.600 --> 04:24:16.600
And that lawsuit, Hamer v. Campbell, 358 F.2d 215, had been filed and was encoded.

04:24:16.600 --> 04:24:20.600
And they had been known that that suit was going to come down.

04:24:20.600 --> 04:24:29.600
So what had happened, Guillard and the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party, what was left of it, had moved the official office,

04:24:30.600 --> 04:24:36.600
state office to sunflower, the small town of sunflower in the Delta.

04:24:36.600 --> 04:24:57.600
And when that march started, that case was Hamer versus Campbell dealing with the right to vote and to be able to participate for blacks to participate in the electoral process.

04:24:57.600 --> 04:25:08.600
That lawsuit set back throughout the elections in two communities in the town of sunflower and in the town of Moorhead, Mississippi.

04:25:08.600 --> 04:25:16.600
And it set up a voter registration period for blacks to get registered and then to hold new elections.

04:25:16.600 --> 04:25:20.600
And so that's what that particular was about.

04:25:21.600 --> 04:25:49.600
Now that we had the FDP office in sunflower and the march was to march against fear about voter registration, Fannie Lou Hamer Hamer set up a march from that small town to Indianola, to the courthouse and asked me and Joe Harris to go and ask Dr. King and Stokely Carmichael to bring the march through the city.

04:25:50.600 --> 04:26:07.600
To deviate from Highway 61 in order to bring it so that blacks in the Delta could get the feel of this big march and hopefully encourage them to register and to vote.

04:26:08.600 --> 04:26:19.600
So we won the approval of Dr. King and that group that they would bring the march along Highway 7 to Greenwood and stayed at night in Greenwood.

04:26:19.600 --> 04:26:35.600
So then a forward group, a group made up of myself, Stokely Carmichael, James Jones and another guy, I'm not sure whether that was Willie Ricks or not.

04:26:35.600 --> 04:26:49.600
But anyway, we were to go and secure a place where we decided Greenwood was it because our history in the Delta was in Greenwood.

04:26:49.600 --> 04:26:59.600
And we had had a lot of things happen there, Travis was shot there, the National SNCC office was located there.

04:26:59.600 --> 04:27:05.600
And so we said we're going to stay in Greenwood.

04:27:05.600 --> 04:27:25.600
So the marches took off, we took off. We got to Greenwood and Stokely Carmichael went to talk to the black leadership there about putting up on a school ground, stone street elementary school or in the black community.

04:27:25.600 --> 04:27:34.600
And we were going to leave and Jones and I went to Mississippi Valley State (College to meet with Mississippi Valley State (College, the president to see about an alternative spot.

04:27:34.600 --> 04:27:40.600
We were so sure we were going to get Greenwood, but we wanted an alternative spot in the case we did not.

04:27:40.600 --> 04:27:47.600
So we would rather put up on that campus anyway because of the kids there.

04:27:47.600 --> 04:27:53.600
So we went to Mississippi Valley State (College, got permission to meet with Mississippi Valley State (College.

04:27:53.600 --> 04:28:01.600
Mississippi Valley State (College told us we could meet with him around three or four o'clock that day in his house.

04:28:01.600 --> 04:28:15.600
So Cleve, James Jones and I went to Mississippi Valley State (College's house and he read us a prepared statement that nine us used to the campus.

04:28:15.600 --> 04:28:20.600
And he's flanked by about eight or ten white state troopers.

04:28:20.600 --> 04:28:23.600
And right after that they run us off the campus.

04:28:23.600 --> 04:28:37.600
And we went back to Greenwood and we learned that Stokely Carmichael is in jail, that he had been arrested for trying to erect a tent on the stone street elementary campus.

04:28:37.600 --> 04:28:47.600
Now Stokely Carmichael had received approval from the black leadership in Greenwood to put up the tent.

04:28:48.600 --> 04:28:58.600
But then the white power there had overruled these blacks and told Stokely Carmichael couldn't put up the tent.

04:28:58.600 --> 04:29:09.600
Of course Stokely Carmichael, the guy that he was and like most of us, it's our school, it's our community.

04:29:09.600 --> 04:29:14.600
He's going to erect a tent anyway. So now he's in jail.

04:29:14.600 --> 04:29:21.600
The marches are on their way to Greenwood, don't know nothing about what's happening in Greenwood.

04:29:21.600 --> 04:29:25.600
They are headed there with the understanding that we're going to be able to put up here.

04:29:25.600 --> 04:29:42.600
Okay, so now that Stokely Carmichael is in jail and the marches are coming, Stokely Carmichael, James Jones, and whoever they saw the party, got together and talked.

04:29:42.600 --> 04:29:49.600
I said that we are going to stay in Greenwood. So how are we going to do it?

04:29:49.600 --> 04:30:04.600
SNCC had once had an office in Greenwood. Our last SNCC office was right around the corner from a big black par that opened on all sides.

04:30:04.600 --> 04:30:09.600
He said, what we're going to do, we're going to put up in this par. He said, well they gave it to him.

04:30:09.600 --> 04:30:19.600
He said, look what we do is we send the run back to meet the marches and tell them to come in the Greenwood by this rock.

04:30:19.600 --> 04:30:26.600
We send them and just tell them what's happening that we're going to stay in Greenwood.

04:30:26.600 --> 04:30:35.600
Don't tell them officials, the highway patrolmen and the local sheriffs and all of them up front and in the real.

04:30:35.600 --> 04:30:42.600
So we went along the route that we wanted them to come when this guy was on his way back.

04:30:42.600 --> 04:30:53.600
Cleve, and James Jones went to get Stokely Carmichael out of jail and the marches are approaching the city limits of Greenwood.

04:30:53.600 --> 04:31:05.600
And we were out there telling people along this route that Stokely Carmichael coming to town, the marches are coming to stay here tonight, get out to the par.

04:31:05.600 --> 04:31:11.600
We were thinking that maybe we'd have a few people because now this park is right in the heart of the black community.

04:31:11.600 --> 04:31:22.600
So we, some people there who knew us from the past agreed to go to houses all around the park and tell them to come to the park.

04:31:22.600 --> 04:31:28.600
Man, when we got there in Stokely Carmichael and the winning got Stokely Carmichael out of jail.

04:31:28.600 --> 04:31:39.600
All the way when he was walking from where we had, the crowd was so big that we had to park the car and walk to the park.

04:31:39.600 --> 04:31:42.600
And about two streets, three streets over.

04:31:42.600 --> 04:31:47.600
Now the policemen were out there on the highway.

04:31:47.600 --> 04:31:54.600
They didn't know what happened while the marches disappeared, you know, from from from from following them.

04:31:54.600 --> 04:31:58.600
And then the ones behind trying to communicate with them.

04:31:58.600 --> 04:32:05.600
But by now we are in Greenwood and circling that park and the world we had told them that as soon as you circled the park,

04:32:05.600 --> 04:32:09.600
stop your cars, jump out and fill up the park.

04:32:09.600 --> 04:32:13.600
But the park's now all ready for the people there in Greenwood.

04:32:13.600 --> 04:32:16.600
So now we just got that whole area.

04:32:16.600 --> 04:32:19.600
And so somebody said, well, what are they going to do?

04:32:19.600 --> 04:32:22.600
They said, well, they'll have to kill us all.

04:32:22.600 --> 04:32:26.600
And what would the and the news media is there now.

04:32:26.600 --> 04:32:31.600
You remember now Stokely Carmichael coming all the way there.

04:32:31.600 --> 04:32:44.600
And he said, we, us black people, can't do nothing that the white people can't take away from us.

04:32:44.600 --> 04:32:47.600
He said, we ain't got no counter-power.

04:32:47.600 --> 04:32:49.600
We need some black power.

04:32:49.600 --> 04:32:52.600
We need some black power all the way there.

04:32:52.600 --> 04:33:00.600
And soon as he stepped up there on the stage with the target and mentioned the black power, the news media.

04:33:00.600 --> 04:33:06.600
They defined black power for us as you know, immediately.

04:33:06.600 --> 04:33:18.600
And so Stokely Carmichael, but now you know black power originally came for Willie Ricks, one of Stokely Carmichael's comrades, who had been talking about black power all along.

04:33:18.600 --> 04:33:23.600
But now you think about this in Fannie Lou Hamer, defined black power for us.

04:33:23.600 --> 04:33:25.600
You think about this.

04:33:25.600 --> 04:33:41.600
You're talking about registering blacks to vote in rural Alabama, rural Georgia, where we are majority of the population, and in bigger cities, where we are majority.

04:33:41.600 --> 04:33:45.600
Now what are you going to get out of that?

04:33:45.600 --> 04:33:50.600
You got thousands of blacks, hundreds of blacks who never registered to vote.

04:33:50.600 --> 04:33:56.600
Now they're getting the chance to register voter as a result of the voting rights act and federal registrals.

04:33:56.600 --> 04:34:02.600
Now black voters are going to be black power.

04:34:02.600 --> 04:34:08.600
I mean, Stokely Carmichael said if we had said color power, everything would have been alright.

04:34:08.600 --> 04:34:13.600
But the word black frightened people.

04:34:13.600 --> 04:34:17.600
And black power.

04:34:17.600 --> 04:34:24.600
And so my paper talks about what happened, how we did that.

04:34:24.600 --> 04:34:29.600
And about King coming to speaking in the middle of the meeting, Fannie Lou Ham was group.

04:34:29.600 --> 04:34:31.600
Fannie Lou had to go somewhere else.

04:34:31.600 --> 04:34:33.600
She was not at the meeting at the courthouse.

04:34:33.600 --> 04:34:34.600
I was there.

04:34:34.600 --> 04:34:44.600
And if you look at that marker, at the par, there I am standing right there by Stokely Carmichael.

04:34:44.600 --> 04:34:56.600
See, when Stokely Carmichael came into office, he named me one of his comrades in Mississippi and gave me the responsibility to pull together his people in his folk in Mississippi

04:34:56.600 --> 04:35:01.600
and bring all of our cars and things into one location.

04:35:01.600 --> 04:35:04.600
And then who to go from that.

04:35:04.600 --> 04:35:23.600
So black power got to frighten people as a result of the media because after all, I consider what we have now, especially in these areas, is black power.

04:35:23.600 --> 04:35:33.600
And black power only means, Miss Amy said, that we want to help determine some of our destiny to have something to say about our lives.

04:35:33.600 --> 04:35:44.600
It's the media and the scared people who got frightened about that because all Americans have the right to vote.

04:35:44.600 --> 04:35:49.600
I mean, the vote, it's the essence of our democracy.

04:35:49.600 --> 04:35:56.600
So there ought not to be a need for a voting rights act.

04:35:56.600 --> 04:35:57.600
Why?

04:35:57.600 --> 04:36:02.600
Because all Americans ought to be able to vote.

04:36:02.600 --> 04:36:13.600
And it ought not to be, and it ought to be such an amendment that forbids anybody to just take you.

04:36:13.600 --> 04:36:16.600
You know, states ought not to be allowed to take it.

04:36:16.600 --> 04:36:23.600
It ought to be a national effort because it's America.

04:36:23.600 --> 04:36:28.600
But we wouldn't have Barack Obama in office if we didn't get, hadn't got a little power.

04:36:28.600 --> 04:36:40.600
And you know, freedom somewhere and all of this with these young white people coming down here that young people in this country put the boy in office.

04:36:40.600 --> 04:36:41.600
All right.

04:36:41.600 --> 04:36:42.600
Thank you.

04:36:42.600 --> 04:36:46.600
Thank you for coming and recalling this.

04:36:46.600 --> 04:36:55.600
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
